      else:\n            bins[i] = bins[i] + item\n    return bins\n\nThis code uses loops and conditionals which are forbidden.\n\n### How to Ensure Vectorization:\nUse numpy operations that work on the entire array without loops or conditionals.\n\n### How to Test:\nAfter writing each function, you can test it with sample inputs.\n\n### Sample Test Code:\n\nimport numpy as np\n\nbins = np.array([5.0, 3.0, 8.0])\nitem = 2.0\n\npriority_scores = priority(item, bins)\n\nprint(priority_scores)\n\nExpected Output:\nAn array of the same size as bins, with each element representing the priority score.\n\n### Task:\nGenerate 10 unique functions as described.\n\n### Additional Hints:\n- Use numpy functions that can operate on arrays.\n- Combine different mathematical operations in unique ways.\n- Consider different mathematical functions and their properties.\n- Think about different ways to represent the priority based on the item and bins.\n\n### Conclusion:\nEach function must be unique and use a different combination of allowed operations to compute the priority scores.\n</think>\n\n### Implementation 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item) * (np.log(bins + 1) + np.sin(np.pi * bins)) + np.sqrt(item)\n\n### Implementation 2:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item * np.mean(bins)) * np.std(bins) + np.tanh(np.pi * item)\n\n### Implementation 3:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item + np.mean(bins)) * (np.log(item) + np.cos(bins)) + np.sqrt(item)\n\n### Implementation 4:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.log(item + np.sum(bins)) * np.std(bins) + np.tanh(np.pi * item)\n\n### Implementation 5:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item - np.mean(bins)) * (np.log(item) + np.sin(bins)) + np.sqrt(item)\n\n### Implementation 6:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: n